  "answer": "Both volumes belong to Charles Comte's Traité de Législation. Vol I, chapter 1 (charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-i-7e62a2, ch.1, p-6a39c9) opens with a methodological declaration: 'I wish simply to investigate the causes that make a people prosper or decline, or that render it stationary' — the entire chapter then defends the analytical/observational method against theological, philosophical, and jurisconsult rivals, leaving the meaning of 'prosperity' and 'decline' undefined. Vol II, chapter 1 (charles-comte-traite-de-legislation-vol-ii-20331d, ch.1, p-d9a82b) opens by directly recalling that goal: 'The object of this work being to expound what are the principal causes of the prosperity and decadence of nations, it is suitable, before making this exposition, to determine the meaning one attaches to these words of decadence and prosperity.' It then systematically defines perfectionnement and dégradation at three levels — physical organs, intellectual faculties, and moral affections — before scaling up from individual to family, nation, and humanity. Vol II ch.1 also explicitly cites Vol I as the 'preceding book' in which man was already 'considered from three different points of view' (p-c5ad71), showing the continuity is deliberate. The emphasis has not genuinely shifted: Vol II is not a pivot but a completion of what Vol I's method demanded. Vol I announced the goal and established how to reason; Vol II does the definitional groundwork that the analytical method requires before causal claims can be made — you cannot observe causes of 'prosperity' without first fixing the meaning of the term. The perfectionnement/dégradation framing is the analytical method applied to anthropology, exactly as Vol I promised it would be applied to legislation. The arch is continuous; Vol II sharpens what Vol I had already implied.",
